<figureCitation box="[628,713,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
) wholly with sparse punctures; vertex with deep and dense to moderate punctures, POD 1.0× OOD; pronotal anterior carina (
<figureCitation box="[862,991,366,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Figs 59, 60</figureCitation>
) medially minutely absent, and dorsum of pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[306,387,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Fig. 59</figureCitation>
) anteriorly with dense punctures and posteriorly with moderate punctures; lateral side of pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[238,319,439,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
) ventrally striate; ventral surface of mid femur smooth, without punctures nor setae; each of T1–T6 except base yellow; T3–T5 (
<figureCitation box="[466,546,475,502]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
) basally with dense punctures, apical one-third impunctate and smooth; T7 (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-187@14.[151,1436,597,1924]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Meria askhabadensis, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) anteriorly with moderate punctures and posteriorly with sparse punctures, and apex with notch and tipped lobes rounded.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641342" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6641342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641342/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="166" startId="14.[151,264,1947,1971]" targetBox="[151,1435,598,1917]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1947,2007]" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,341,1947,1971]" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">FIGURES 57–62.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1886" box="[348,565,1947,1971]" class="Insecta" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Meria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="askhabadensis">
<emphasis box="[348,565,1947,1971]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="166">Meria askhabadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, ♂. 57. Habitus, dorsal view; 58. Head, frontal view; 59. Pronotum, dorsal view; 60. Pronotum, lateral view; 61. T3–T5, dorsal view; 62. T7, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="167">
Female. Head distinctly wider than the high in frontal view, rounded behind the eyes; head and pronotum dark red; dorsum of propodeum basally striate laterally, and medially largely impunctate; T2–T4 laterally with light spots, and the distance between two lateral spots equal to the length of the spot. No female specimens were collected in our study, so description is referred to 
<bibRefCitation author="Radoszkowski, O." box="[611,858,259,286]" pageId="15" pageNumber="167" pagination="3 - 56" refId="ref16918" refString="Radoszkowski, O. (1886) Faune hymenopterologique Transcaspienne. Horae Societatis entomologicae Rossicae, 20, 3 - 56." type="journal article" year="1886">Radoszkowski (1886)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
